audio_descriptions.notes:
"Simon's Cat in 'staircase' sponsored by Wix.com." 
This black and white cartoon features pet owner Simon and his cat. Simon is middle-aged, medium built, and has spiky hair. His fluffy, white cat has a pointed ears and large, thick tail. Both are drawn with exaggerated, circular eyes. 
The video opens on a staircase beside a wall with two framed pictures of birds. All action takes place here.

Simon wobbles down the staircase, concentrated on carrying a cardboard box overflowing with his belongings. His cat follows behind, holding a toy bird in its mouth, identical to the birds pictured on the wall. 

The cat pauses halfway down, sadly watching Simon walk away. It sits on all fours gnawing on the squeaking bird toy. 

The cat suddenly drops the toy, which bounces down the stairs. Simon approaches and quickly dodges the toy. 

Eager to play with Simon, the cat blocks his path to return upstairs. 

Simon motions for the cat to move, but it remains in its place, gazing up at its owner. Simon looks befuddled as his cat sits down. 

Simon throws his hands up and asks his cat to move. 

The cat playfully reaches for Simon's hands, then lays down.

Simon tries to walk around his cat, but it anticipates all his movements and blocks his path accordingly. 

Simon turns sideways and his cat moves over. Pressed against the wall, Simon slinks up the stairs. The cat glides up and down Simon's moving leg.

Simon retracts his leg and continues up the stairs, as the cat falls and lands on its head, looking shocked. It recovers and faces the top of the staircase, awaiting Simon's return.

Simon descends the stairs carrying a sealed box, as his cat happily marches in place.

The cat rubs against Simon's leg. Simon tries to push the cat out of the way with his foot, but is unsuccessful. Simon yells.

Instead of moving, the cat abruptly lays down on the steps, eyes closed and body completely stretched out. Looking cute, it slowly plops down the stairs and rests at the bottom. Simon follows behind apprehensively. He grunts in frustration.

Trying not to disturb the peaceful cat, Simon steps over it, but lands on the squeaky toy, causing the cat to stir. 

The cat sits up and smiles at Simon, who shoots it an angry look and walks off, leaving the cat sad.

The cat steps on its toy as it runs up the steps, stopping in the middle of the staircase. With a longing look, it lays on its stomach, then licks its paw contently.

Simon re-enters, walking towards the cat. They pause and stare at each other.

The cat lovingly turns on its back, showing its stomach and purring.

Simon looks up and down the stairs, as if planning how to move past his cat.

The cat stretches and smacks its lips happily. Simon creeps up the stairs with his back hunched.

As soon as Simon steps over the cat, it latches onto his pant leg with its claws, trying to pull Simon back. 

Simon trudges up the stairs, dragging the cat clinging to his leg. When Simon reaches the top, he moves his leg and the cat releases. It lays on its stomach, defeated.

Hearing a noise, the cat excitedly crouches and waves its tail. Simon comes to the top of the stairs with another box.

Suddenly, the cat pounces on Simon, and the two bounce down the stairs, looking horribly frightened. 

The cat climbs over Simon's face and sits back on the stairs. Simon rises and finds the toy bird beneath him.

Simon lightly shakes the cardboard box and hears broken glass. 

He scowls at his cat, who marches in place happily. 

Simon walks off. His cat looks disappointed.

A soccer ball appears at the top of the stairs and rolls down to the cat. 

The cat looks puzzled, glancing in different directions. A sleigh bell rolls down to him, then a tennis ball, further scaring the cat.

A small kitten appears at the top step, grinning down at the cat. 

The kitten begins marching in place. The cat excitedly marches with the kitten. Simon's eyes widen in confusion.  

Simon finally gives up on going upstairs and walks away. The cat looks upset, and the kitten throws a ball at its head.

The cat turns toward the kitten angrily. The kitten runs away and the cat stumbles up the stairs, then runs out of view. 

The screen fades to white. An ad for Wix.com begins, featuring a montage with the characters from Simon's Cat.

AD:

Simon looks at his adorable cat surrounded by tiny stars, its eyes beaming.

In another scene, Simon beams with pride, donning a t-shirt with his cat's face on it, as the cat looks at it skeptically.

Simon and his cat face a large house filled with cats and a heart above the doorway.

Simon works at his computer with his affectionate cat. The cat blocks the screen as Simon types a blog. Simon gently moves the cat out of the way.

Simon scrolls through Wix.com's website.

Simon's cat unplugs his computer and runs to his side, grinning, as Simon freaks out!

Simon angrily opens a door and places his cat outside. 

Simon is shown at his computer. His cat reappears and blocks the screen again.

Wix.com is shown again. The screen fades to white and the credits are shown, accompanied by a picture of Simon's cat and social media links.

FAQs:

Q. What software do you use?
A. Simon's Cat has been made using a variety of animation software over the years. Originally in Adobe Flash. Then TV Paint (and still on occasions) and most recently using CelAction.

Q. Why does it take so long to make each Simon's Cat film?
A. Animation is a slow process and Simon’s Cat films pay particular attention to observed, real life cat behaviour. Historically the films were traditionally animated frame by frame. More recently we use CelAction which has sped up the process but still requires a lot of care and attention. Each film takes approximately 6-9 weeks to make, depending on complexity, number of characters and special effects.
